comment_text: I'm doing a Masters in chemistry and I can tell you that the absorption wavelengths of PH3 are unique and you can think about them as a fingerprint of the chemical. However a single wavelength can be mistaken for another chemical's if the measurement is not precise enough. I don't know if these people have measured a single wavelength or more and how precise they did it. Hope this helps.

comment_text:
Nice. Be very interesting to know how confident they are that the measurement is from PH3 - like on that Sigma scale thingo. So we have two things - is it really PH3, and, if it is PH3, is it really being created by life. I'd love to eliminate the first question by having other groups look at the data and 100% confirm that it is absolutely PH3. Then we've just got the second question.
I wonder if others are now trying to repeat the detection with their instruments - or did this original group use the best/most sensitive hardware for the first detection so therefore no one else could get anymore sensitive/get better data.
It "worries" me that Venus is a hot and pressurised environ so we are missing some other non-life associated reaction that is bonding hydrogen to phosphorus - but they seemed to have really researched this and can't fins a pathway..
EDIT: was just thinking about an ongoing study that would track the PH3 over a year to map out the concentrations and places over the atmosphere. Wonder what might be gained from that - although of course it is always so low on the horizon. Maybe a dedicated, simple-ish satellite in one of those weird orbits that never puts the earth in the way of the target, and it just continually does the measurement over the disk. I'm procrastinating by writing comments. cheers.
